<section xml:id="section-quadratic-functions">
  <title>Quadratic Functions</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The next <q>flavor</q> of functions following linear functions is
      <term>quadratic functions</term>. In this section, we familiarize ourselves with their
      features and some vocabulary.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Quadratic Function Formulas</title>
    <p>
      A function <m>f</m> is <term>quadratic</term> if it has a formula in the form
      <md>
        f(x)=ax^2+bx+c
      </md>
      for some numbers <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>. While <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are allowed to
      be <m>0</m>, the number <m>a</m> must not be <m>0</m> (or else we would just have a linear
      function).
    </p>
    <example>
      <title>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>